11.content:
IMPORTANT INFORMATION

Your goal is to select the winning racecar as often as you can.
The performance of each racecar changes from race to race.
The only way to predict the winning racecar is by understanding what the symbols tell you about how the performance of each racecar compares to the performance of the sample racecar in that particular race.

To select the winning racecar, pay attention to the sample racecar and the symbols in the boxes at the bottom of the screen. Use the information provided to select the winning racecar as often as you can.

In the beginning this task will involve some trial and error. Please be patient and try your best to select the winning racecar.
You will see in the race if you guessed correctly. To make sure you know whether you selected the winner, you will be told after each race if you selected the winning racecar.

Good luck!

Click to continue.

25.content:
Informed Consent

You may need to scroll down to see all the text on this screen.


Project Title: Learning

Overview and Procedures: The purpose of this study is to investigate how we learn. You will see screens with containing symbols. Sometimes you will need to respond to what is presented on screen.

Risk and Benefits. This study involves no more risk to your physical or psychological health beyond those encountered in the normal course of everyday life. You may benefit by gaining a better understanding of psychological research. No other risks or benefits are anticipated.

Confidentiality. Any information obtained in this study will be kept strictly confidential and used solely for research purposes. We do not ask any identifying information and responses will be kept completely anonymous. Your anonymised data may be posted to a public repository for other researchers to make use of.

Compensation. You will receive a sum of money for participating.

Your Rights. Your decision to participate in this research is voluntary. You can withdraw from the study at any time without penalty. You do not have to answer any questions you do not want to.

Contact Information. If you have any questions or issues with this study please contact the principle investigator (Martin Finn) at martin.finn@ugent.be who can review the matter and provide further information.

You must be 18 years of age or older to participate in this research study.

Please let the experimenter know if you would like a copy of this form for your records.

If you want to continue press the button.

89.content:
Debriefing

Thank you for completing the study!

You may need to scroll down to see all the text on this screen.

The purpose of this study is to investigate how we learn. At the beginning we paired two symbols with the words "same" and "different". Later we combined these symbols with other symbols that communicated information about each racecar's performance. You were asked to try select the winning racecar for each race, and were provided feedback for your choices. In this way the meaning of the new symbols might have become clear. You might have noticed that one of the new symbols signified "speed" while the other symbol signified "direction". You may not have noticed this, and that is the reason for this study.

The specific purpose of this study was to discover whether the training we provided allowed the symbols to communicate information about the racecars' performances. If the winning racecars were selected consistently then the symbols used in this study did indeed operate as symbols.

There is a more general purpose too. As described above, the final part of the study involves multiple symbols and interactions between them. We are constantly interacting with symbols (e.g., words, numbers, road-signs etc). Our more general purpose is to discover how we learn to respond appropriately to symbols and the interactions between them. I hope that makes things clear! If you have any questions about the study you can email me at martin.finn@ugent.be

Click to continue.

Study guidelines


Make sure you do this experiment on a laptop or regular desktop computer and NOT on a smartphone or tablet. You will need a keyboard and mouse for this experiment.

Do not close this tab and do not switch to other tabs during the experiment. It is important that you remain attentive. In this way you help us to make this research valuable.

In this study you will learn how to complete some tasks. You will see a sequence of screens. On some screens you must respond by selecting either E or I on your keyboard. On other screens you will select options using your mouse. Sometimes you will be provided with feedback for your response - but not always!

Learn how to respond accurately. Then respond as accurately as you can.

143.content:
Debriefing

Thank you for completing the study!

You may need to scroll down to see all the text on this screen.

The purpose of this study is to investigate how we learn. As you will have seen, throughout the study a sequence of screens is presented; first, either a rectangle or a triangle, this is followed by three circles in two different colors and you pick one of these coloured circles (the matching or the non-matching color), and finally you are provided feedback for your choice. When one shape was presented, choosing the matching color resulted in feedback saying 'Correct!', and when the other was presented choosing the non-matching color resulted in feedback saying 'Correct!'. In this way, the two shapes signalled the relationship between the circles of different colors.

There is a more general purpose too. Our more general purpose is to discover how we learn to respond appropriately to symbols and the interactions between them. I hope that makes things clear! If you have any questions about the study you can email me at martin.finn@ugent.be

Click to continue.
